'''Marrecs de Salt''' ({{IPA-ca|məˈrɛɡz ðə ˈsal}}) is a group of [[castellers]] (human tower builders) from [[Salt, Girona]] ([[Catalonia]]) founded in 1995. They are also to be considered as the local group in Girona,<ref name="twoCities">{{cite news|title=Una colla, dues ciutats|newspaper=Revista Castells|url=http://revistacastells.cat/2013/07/una-colla-dues-ciutats/|date=30 July 2013|language=catalan}}</ref> together with their university counterpart: [[Xoriguers de la UdG]]. They are one of the seven active groups in the [[province of Girona]] and since the dissolution of [[Castellers de l'Albera]], also the oldest. Their best human tower is the [[5 in 8]] and their best performance was on 27 October 2013 for the performance of Sant Narcís in the city of Girona, were they completed the [[4 in 8]], the [[2 in 8 with double base]], the [[3 in 8]] and the [[pillar of 6]]. Their shirt is blue standing for the [[Ter (river)|river Ter]], which flows through both Salt and Girona, as well as other regions of the province.

== History ==
[[File:Pilar de la Catedral de Girona 2012.jpg|thumb|Pillar of the [[Cathedral of Girona|Cathedral]], [[Girona]]]]
The group was founded in 1995, mainly influenced by a performance by [[Castellers de Terrassa]] and [[Castellers d'Esparreguera]] in Plaça del Vi, in [[Girona]] on the celebrations of Sant Narcís.<ref>{{cite news|title=Un grup de veïns de Salt projecta crear una colla castellera|newspaper=[[El Punt]]|date=3 November 1995|language=catalan}}</ref> Their first public appearance was 5 January 1996 in Salt, where they crowned a [[pillar of 4]] and completed a [[pillar of 4 raised]].<ref name=3WiseMen>{{cite news|title=Els Marrecs de Salt ja aixequen castells|newspaper=[[El Punt]]|date=21 December 1995|language=catalan}}</ref> They got ''baptized'' on 14 April 1996 in Salt with Castellers de Terrassa and the disappeared [[Ganxets de Reus]] being their [[godparent]]s.<ref name="baptism">{{cite news|title=Girona entra en el mundo de los "castells" con el bautizo de las "colles" de Salt y la Albera|url=http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.com/preview/1996/04/14/pagina-37/33943957/pdf.html|newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]]|date=14 April 1996|language=spanish}}</ref> On this day Marrecs completed the [[4 in 6 with wedge]], crowned the [[2 in 6]] and completed the [[3 in 6]], while their [[godparents]] completed various towers of 7 levels.<ref name="CCCC">{{cite web|url=http://www.cccc.cat/base-de-dades|title=Base de dades|editor=[[Coordinadora de Colles Castelleres de Catalunya|CCCC]]|language=catalan}}</ref>

The first years of the group, their rehearsals took place in public buildings with other uses such as ''La Farga'' school or the local sports pavilion<ref>{{cite news|title=Cuaderno|publisher=[[El Periódico de Catalunya]]|url=http://archivo.elperiodico.com/ed/19981004/cuaderno/pag_085.html|date=4 October 1998|language=spanish}}</ref> and the first year they used ''cafè de Can Pep'' as their gathering social club.<ref name="baptism" /> The group got better quickly reaching basic structures of seven levels, but the [[4 in 7 with wedge]] and the [[5 in 7]] were not reached until 1997, which was also the first year to perform in the walking pillar of the cathedral performance.<ref name="pillarofthecatedral">{{cite news|title=Els Marrecs van aconseguir pujar amb un pilar de quatre les escales de la Catedral|publisher=[[El Punt]]|date=2 November 1997}}</ref> In 1998 they moved to their premises in [[Factoria Cultural Coma-Cros|Coma-Cros]] and completed their first [[3 in 7 raised]]. The [[2 in 7]] was completed in 1999,  completing what was then considered the full range of seven level towers.

The first time they completed a tower of eight levels was in 2001 in plaça del Vi of Girona, where they completed the [[4 in 8]] and crowned the [[3 in 8]], so far being the only group that begins building towers of eight levels, building two in the same performance.<ref name="29 oct 2001">{{cite news|title=Éxito de los Marrecs|publisher=[[El Periódico de Catalunya|El Periódico]]|url=http://archivo.elperiodico.com/ed/20011029/pag_060.html|date=29 October 2001|language=spanish}}</ref> In 2002, Marrecs and [[Castellers de Sabadell]] became godparents of [[Xerrics d'Olot]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Crònica del Bateig dels Xerrics d'Olot|publisher=[[La Xarxa]]|url=http://www.laxarxa.com/noticia/cronica-del-bateig-dels-xerrics-d-olot|date=13 May 2002|language=catalan}}</ref> This year saw a crowned [[pillar of 6]] and until 2006 they did not succeed completing their first [[3 in 8]]. In 2007, during the [[Fiesta patronal|town's festivities]] of Salt, it was the first time they completed the [[3 in 8]], the [[4 in 8]] and the [[2 in 7]] together in a single performance.

In 2011 the group moved to their current premises in ''Naus Guixeres'' which is also in ''[[Factoria Cultural Coma-Cros|Coma-Cros]]''<ref name="premises" /> and in 2012 they built their first [[2 in 8 with double base]], which ended up being only crowned, together with completed [[3 in 8]] and [[4 in 8]], building three towers of eight levels together in the same performance for their first time.<ref name="28 oct 2012 DdG" /> This performance was overtaken three times during 2013: completing the hat-trick (which in the field stands for the 3, the 4 and the 2 in 8 in the same performance) by completing for the first time the [[2 in 8 with double base]] in July,<ref name="28 jul 2013 LV">{{cite news |url=http://www.diaridegirona.cat/comarques/2013/07/29/marrecs-demostren-maduresa-descarregant-tres/628331.html |title=Els Marrecs demostren maduresa descarregant tres castells de vuit a Salt |publisher=[[Diari de Girona]] |date= 29 July 2013|language=catalan}}</ref> suming up the crowned [[pillar of 6]] at the beginning of October,<ref name="6 oct 2013 DdG" /> and finally completing the [[pillar of 6]] in the [[Diada de Sant Narcís]], on 27 October.<ref name="27 oct 2013 Ara">{{cite news |url=http://www.ara.cat/comarquesgironines/Marrecs-Salt-castellera-Sant-Narcis_0_1018698370.html |title=Els Marrecs de Salt se superen en la diada castellera de Sant Narcís |publisher=[[Diari Ara]] |date= 27 October 2013|language=catalan}}</ref> On 26 October 2014, also on the [[Diada de Sant Narcís|Sant Narcís]], they crowned their first [[5 in 8]].<ref name="5de8(c) 2014">{{cite web|last1=Esteve|first1=Carles|title=Els Marrecs assalten la catedral|publisher=Revista Castells|url=http://revistacastells.cat/index.php/2014/10/els-marrecs-assalten-la-catedral|date=29 October 2014|language=catalan}}</ref> Lately Marrecs have baptized some other groups of castellers that were recently created: in 2013 they baptized [[Esperxats de l'Estany]] having [[Castellers de Figueres]] as co-godparents<ref>{{cite news|title=Els Esperxats de l'Estany fan el seu bateig a la Festa Major de Porqueres|publisher=Banyoles TV|url=http://banyolestv.cat/index.php/noticies/general/societat/item/1008-els-esperxats-de-lestany-fan-el-seu-bateig-a-la-festa-major-de-porqueres|date=20 May 2013|language=catalan}}</ref> and in 2014 they baptized [[Vailets de l'Empordà]] together with [[Minyons de Terrassa]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Els Vailets de l'Empordà estrenen el quatre de set el dia del seu bateig|publisher=[[La Vanguardia]]|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/croniques-castelleres/20140330/54405274398/vailets-emporda-descarreguen-seu-primer-castell-set-pisos.html|date=30 March 2014|language=catalan}}</ref> and [[Castellers de l'Alt Maresme]] together with [[Capgrossos de Mataró]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Maduixots, amunt!|publisher=[[El Punt Avui]]|url=http://www.elpuntavui.cat/noticia/article/5-cultura/19-cultura/736310-maduixots-amunt.html|date=27 April 2014}}</ref> There's another pending [[godson]] group: [[Minyons de Santa Cristina]], to be co-godparented with [[Sagals d'Osona]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Diada nacional a Castell d'Aro|url=http://minyonsdesantacristina.blog.cat/2013/09/12/diada-nacional-a-castell-daro/|editor=[[Minyons de Santa Cristina]]|date=12 September 2013}}</ref>

